<p>
  Project Budget is in early development. These docs grow as features land. For terminology, see the <a href="/glossary/">glossary</a>.
</p>

<h2>Quick start</h2>
<ol>
  <li>Open <a href="/app/">the app</a>.</li>
  <li>Create a profile and give it a name (for example, <em>Household</em>).</li>
  <li>Add your accounts: checking, savings, and any credit cards.</li>
  <li>Create category groups (for example, <em>Immediate Obligations</em>, <em>True Expenses</em>, <em>Quality of Life</em>) and the categories that live under them.</li>
  <li>When money lands in an account as inflow-to-budget, head to the Budget page and assign every dollar a job.</li>
  <li>Enter transactions as you go. Reconcile when your statement arrives.</li>
  <li>Export your profile to JSON periodically as a backup.</li>
</ol>

<h2>How data is stored</h2>
<p>
  Every profile lives in your browser under <code>localStorage</code> keys prefixed with <code>projectbudget:</code>. The active profile id is held at <code>projectbudget:active</code>. The full profile bundle (accounts, transactions, categories, budgets) is at <code>projectbudget:profile:&lt;id&gt;</code>. A daily snapshot is written to <code>projectbudget:backup:&lt;id&gt;:&lt;YYYY-MM-DD&gt;</code> and the last fourteen days are kept.
</p>

<h2>Private browsing</h2>
<p>
  In a private or incognito window, <code>localStorage</code> is typically wiped when the window closes. Project Budget detects this and shows a banner reminding you to export before closing.
</p>

<h2>Multiple profiles</h2>
<p>
  Profiles are completely isolated. You can keep a personal budget, a household budget, and an experimental copy side by side. Switch profiles from the profile menu in the app sidebar.
</p>
